                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Haitian Minister</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-06-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 16, 1905</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 88.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    your note of the 9th instant, in which you state that your government would be
                    glad to know what attitude this government would take toward Syrians, who after
                    becoming naturalized American citizens, should attempt to establish a residence
                    in Haiti.</p>
                <p>In reply, I have the honor to say that your note does not present a case calling
                    for action by this Department, and the Department must refrain from announcing
                    its attitude until the question arises in a case actually presented to it and
                    requiring its action.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">F. B. Loomis.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
